const e="strike-price-expiration",t="Strike Price & Expiration (The Two Choices)",i="7 min",o=[{screen_type:"hook",visual:"üéØüìÖ",headline:"Two decisions will make or break your trade",text:"When you buy a call or put, you must choose: WHAT price (strike) and by WHEN (expiration). Pick wrong, you lose money even if you're right about direction. Let's get this right."},{screen_type:"definition",headline:"Strike Price: Your Line in the Sand",text:"The strike price is the price YOU choose where you want to buy (call) or sell (put) the stock. Higher strike = cheaper call but needs bigger move. Lower strike = more expensive call but easier to profit. You're literally picking your target.",visual:"üéØ",highlight_words:["strike price","YOU choose","target"]},{screen_type:"analogy",headline:"Think of it like betting on weather",text:"It's 70¬∞F today. You bet it'll be hotter next week. You have to pick a temperature threshold and a deadline...",interactive:"tap_to_reveal",reveal_sections:[{label:"Bet: Above 75¬∞F by Friday ($10 bet)",content:"Easy target, close deadline. Cheaper bet, easier to win. If it hits 76¬∞F, you win - but not by much."},{label:"Bet: Above 90¬∞F by next month ($2 bet)",content:"Hard target, more time. Very cheap bet, but needs a BIG move. If it hits 91¬∞F, you win big because it was unlikely."},{label:"This is strike selection",content:"Close strikes = expensive, easier to profit. Far strikes = cheap, need big moves. Match your strike to your conviction!"}]},{screen_type:"definition",headline:"Expiration Date: Your Countdown Clock",text:"Every option has an expiration date - usually a Friday. After 4pm ET that day, your option is worthless if not exercised. Short expiration = cheaper but risky (need quick moves). Long expiration = expensive but safer (more time to be right).",visual:"‚è∞",highlight_words:["expiration date","Friday","4pm ET","worthless"]},{screen_type:"key_terms",headline:"Common Expiration Terms",cards:[{term:"Weeklies",definition:"Options expiring this Friday or next",example:"TSLA $250 call expiring in 3 days. Cheap ($50), but needs FAST movement. High risk/reward."},{term:"Monthlies",definition:"Options expiring 30-90 days out",example:"AAPL $180 call expiring in 60 days. Moderate price ($500), gives you time to be right. Most popular."},{term:"LEAPS",definition:"Long-term options (1+ years out)",example:"MSFT $400 call expiring in 12 months. Expensive ($3,000+), but works like stock. Low risk."}]},{screen_type:"multiple_choice",question:"AAPL is at $180. You buy a $200 call (strike above current price). What must happen to profit?",options:["AAPL just needs to go up at all","AAPL needs to go above $200 + the premium you paid","AAPL needs to hit exactly $200","You can't profit if strike is above current price"],correct:1,xp_reward:10,explanation_correct:"Exactly! You need stock above $200 PLUS your premium. If you paid $5 premium, you need AAPL above $205 to profit. $200-$205 = you break even. This is your breakeven price.",explanation_wrong:"Remember: you paid a premium for the option. To PROFIT, the stock needs to exceed strike + premium. If strike is $200 and you paid $5, you need $205+. Otherwise you're just recovering costs."},{screen_type:"multiple_choice",question:"TSLA is at $250. You're bullish long-term. Which is LEAST risky?",options:["$300 call expiring in 2 days","$260 call expiring in 90 days","$400 call expiring in 7 days","All options have the same risk"],correct:1,xp_reward:10,explanation_correct:"Right! Close to the money ($260 vs $250 stock) + lots of time (90 days) = lower risk. You have time for your thesis to play out. The others need massive moves in days - that's gambling, not investing.",explanation_wrong:"Think about probability. Far strikes ($400) need huge moves. Short expiration (2-7 days) needs IMMEDIATE moves. The $260 strike in 90 days only needs a 4% move upward + you have 3 months. That's realistic!"},{screen_type:"scenario",question:"It's Monday. Earnings are Thursday after close. You're very bullish on the report. What expiration do you choose?",options:["This Friday (3 days after earnings)","Next Friday (10 days after earnings)","30 days out","90 days out"],correct:0,xp_reward:15,explanation_correct:"Smart! Earnings = immediate price move. You want the SHORTEST expiration to capture that move at lowest cost. This Friday captures the post-earnings pop. Longer expirations waste money on time you don't need.",explanation_wrong:"Earnings create immediate volatility. You need short-dated options (this Friday) because: 1) They're cheaper, 2) You'll know by Friday if you're right, 3) No point paying for extra time if the move happens Thursday. Match expiration to your catalyst!"},{screen_type:"scenario",question:"You think AI stocks will boom over the next year, but timing is uncertain. Best approach?",options:["Weekly options - keep rolling them forward","60-90 day options","LEAPS (1 year+)","2-day options for max leverage"],correct:1,xp_reward:15,explanation_correct:"Good choice! 60-90 days gives you time without overpaying. If wrong, you haven't spent as much as LEAPS. If right, you capture good returns. This is the 'sweet spot' for directional trades.",explanation_wrong:"Think balanced risk/reward. Weeklies = too risky if timing uncertain. LEAPS = too expensive for speculation. 60-90 days hits the middle: enough time for your thesis to play out, not overpaying for excess time you may not need."},{screen_type:"summary_cards",headline:"Strike & Expiration Strategy",cards:[{front:"How to choose your strike?",back:"Close to current price = expensive but likely. Far from price = cheap but needs big move. Match strike to your conviction level."},{front:"How to choose expiration?",back:"Known catalyst (earnings) = short expiration. Uncertain timing = 60-90 days. Long-term thesis = LEAPS. Match timeframe to your thesis!"},{front:"The golden rule",back:"Give yourself MORE time than you think you need. Most beginners lose by being RIGHT on direction but WRONG on timing. Time = insurance."}]},{screen_type:"celebration",xp_earned:70,total_xp:200,badge:"üéØ Strike Selector",badge_description:"You can pick strikes and expirations strategically!",celebration_message:"Excellent! You now understand the two most important choices in options. Next: understanding what you're actually paying for.",streak_bonus:!1,next_lesson_preview:{title:"Premium: Intrinsic vs Time Value",description:"Learn why options decay and how to use it to your advantage",unlock_status:"unlocked"}}],r={lesson_id:e,title:t,estimated_time:i,screens:o};export{r as default,i as estimated_time,e as lesson_id,o as screens,t as title};
